<Callout type="insight" title="Interactive components are where a11y is won or lost">

Anyone can make a div that toggles. The gap between junior and senior work shows up in the details
your sample components include: `aria-expanded` on the accordion trigger, `role="dialog"` and
`aria-modal` plus focus trapping on the modal, Escape-to-close, an `aria-live` region for toasts, and
motion that backs off under `prefers-reduced-motion`. These aren't extras — for an interactive
component they're part of *correct*. When you review a PR adding a modal, the first questions are
"where does focus go, how does it close with a keyboard, and what does a screen reader announce?" Make
those questions reflexive and your interactive UI will be genuinely usable by everyone.

</Callout>

## Knowledge check

<Quiz
	question="A modal opens visually but keyboard users get stuck behind it. What's missing?"
	options={[
		{ text: 'A bigger z-index', correct: false },
		{ text: 'Focus management — move focus into the modal, trap it, and restore on close', correct: true },
		{ text: 'A longer transition', correct: false },
		{ text: 'A darker backdrop', correct: false }
	]}
	explanation="Accessible modals move focus in, trap it while open, close on Escape, and return focus to the trigger."
/>

## Recap & module wrap-up

Module 8 complete. You can animate state with Tailwind, mount/unmount with Svelte transitions, drive
motion from scroll with CSS, and build accessible interactive components — without sacrificing
performance or inclusivity.

Next module: **Advanced Layout & Patterns** — subgrid, container queries, sticky patterns and
internationalised layouts.
